      },
      "date": "2018-05-03 05:59:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nis this commit still making sense? I mean after https://review.whamcloud.com/30192 was landed",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "bdfc9ee2bea14dd11a2f1a6b6cceef42f8677450",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2018-05-03 13:56:38.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> is this commit still making sense? I mean after https://review.whamcloud.com/30192 was landed\n\nWell it needs to be rebased and half of it has already landed. I think that if we are aggressive then we could have a layered page that uses a 256 byte slab rather than 512. Which would be good. I don't have much time to push on this at the moment though.\n\nThere has also been some discussion of making a single Lustre client module. Or of having fewer modules (say combining llite, lov, osc, lmv, mdc into a single module) and removing the obd and cl method wrappers from the client. I have mixed feelings about this. But if we throw away the abstraction layers then we can have cl_page that uses less then 256 bytes for sure.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "8da2f2e6bbb2eabf4ac9d4f211f4279756023a25",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
